# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: StoryBeginnings | Scene: MeetingOnTheBattlements
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah was slowly walking across the battlements of Castle Reinmeer."
    new "Sarah was slowly walking across the battlements of Castle Reinmeer."

    old "From a distance, she could still hear the sounds of the funeral. The endless kind words she couldn't stand right now."
    new "From a distance, she could still hear the sounds of the funeral. The endless kind words she couldn't stand right now."

    old "Ever since her father had returned home, the cold had grown harsher with each day."
    new "Ever since her father had returned home, the cold had grown harsher with each day."

    old "Sarah loved the summer, but today, she was happy for the stinging cold and the few snowflakes drifting in the wind. Dark clouds in the sky."
    new "Sarah loved the summer, but today, she was happy for the stinging cold and the few snowflakes drifting in the wind. Dark clouds in the sky."

    old "Seems right, Sarah thought to herself, that the world looks this bleak without your father. Nature itself mourns your passing."
    new "Seems right, Sarah thought to herself, that the world looks this bleak without your father. Nature itself mourns your passing."

    old "Looking out out over the edge of the battlements, Sarah saw the many lights of the city, cutting through the dark. Beyond that, the great forests where she used to play as a child."
    new "Looking out out over the edge of the battlements, Sarah saw the many lights of the city, cutting through the dark. Beyond that, the great forests where she used to play as a child."

    old "Would she have another day as free of care as she did back then? As she did even only a week ago?"
    new "Would she have another day as free of care as she did back then? As she did even only a week ago?"

    old "So consumed in busy work, Sarah had not paid much attention to the questions that still needed to be answered."
    new "So consumed in busy work, Sarah had not paid much attention to the questions that still needed to be answered."

    old "Her brother would soon become king, and she knew that he would need her help. But what did either of them know of ruling a nation?"
    new "Her brother would soon become king, and she knew that he would need her help. But what did either of them know of ruling a nation?"

    old "Already, in the days before the funeral, people had begun to approach her. Servants of all ranks, trying to procure favor with her."
    new "Already, in the days before the funeral, people had begun to approach her. Servants of all ranks, trying to procure favor with her."

    old "She could keep them away, on account of her grief, but she knew that soon, the burdens of rule would truly fall on them."
    new "She could keep them away, on account of her grief, but she knew that soon, the burdens of rule would truly fall on them."

    old "And none of that even began to deal questions, such as who was responsible for her father's death."
    new "And none of that even began to deal questions, such as who was responsible for her father's death."

    old "Dad...do you think we're ready?"
    new "Dad...do you think we're ready?"

    old "The howling winds were her only answer."
    new "The howling winds were her only answer."

    old "Excuse me, but can I offer you my cloak?"
    new "Excuse me, but can I offer you my cloak?"

    old "Sarah turned, surprised by the voice. She sees a tall man standing on the battlements next to her."
    new "Sarah turned, surprised by the voice. She sees a tall man standing on the battlements next to her."

    old "It's too cold for you to be out here in nothing more than a dress."
    new "It's too cold for you to be out here in nothing more than a dress."

    old "The man holds out a thick black cloak, large enough to envelop her completely, fashioned out of a wolf skin."
    new "The man holds out a thick black cloak, large enough to envelop her completely, fashioned out of a wolf skin."

    old "It's okay, I don't mind the cold. I like it."
    new "It's okay, I don't mind the cold. I like it."

    old "I understand, but it's colder than you think. Hypothermia can sneak up on you."
    new "I understand, but it's colder than you think. Hypothermia can sneak up on you."

    old "The man pushes his cloak into Sarah's hands."
    new "The man pushes his cloak into Sarah's hands."

    old "Sarah, if only to not embarrass the man, accepts and puts on the cloak."
    new "Sarah, if only to not embarrass the man, accepts and puts on the cloak."

    old "Thank you, kind sir."
    new "Thank you, kind sir."

    old "No problem at all, uhm, my lady. My liege? Princess?"
    new "No problem at all, uhm, my lady. My liege? Princess?"

    old "The man stumbles, trying to find the words."
    new "The man stumbles, trying to find the words."

    old "It's ok, kind sir, don't mind the formalities. My name is Sarah Rose."
    new "It's ok, kind sir, don't mind the formalities. My name is Sarah Rose."

    old "I know who you are."
    new "I know who you are."

    old "A short pause."
    new "A short pause."

    old "And...you are?"
    new "And...you are?"

    old "The man seems flustered."
    new "The man seems flustered."

    old "I'm so sorry, of course, my name is Varga. Varga Northwood."
    new "I'm so sorry, of course, my name is Varga. Varga Northwood."

    old "Sarah observes the man."
    new "Sarah observes the man."

    old "He's tall, black hair, kept short and kempt, the way a soldier would."
    new "He's tall, black hair, kept short and kempt, the way a soldier would."

    old "A large scar runs across the side of his cheek, blemishing what would otherwise be a very handsome face."
    new "A large scar runs across the side of his cheek, blemishing what would otherwise be a very handsome face."

    old "Sir Northwood...I can't say I'm familiar with that family name. What part of Rosanna do you hail from?"
    new "Sir Northwood...I can't say I'm familiar with that family name. What part of Rosanna do you hail from?"

    old "The man looks away, seemingly embarassed."
    new "The man looks away, seemingly embarassed."

    old "Well...the woods up north, actually. Mine is what you could call a more recent addition to the noble families."
    new "Well...the woods up north, actually. Mine is what you could call a more recent addition to the noble families."

    old "Sarah suddenly understands. That explains. Newly promoted nobility, equal in title but lacking the years of experience in protocol."
    new "Sarah suddenly understands. That explains. Newly promoted nobility, equal in title but lacking the years of experience in protocol."

    old "I'm sorry if I'm messing this up, it's my first time at such a formal event."
    new "I'm sorry if I'm messing this up, it's my first time at such a formal event."

    old "It's alright."
    new "It's alright."

    old "Sarah gently puts her hand on the man's arm."
    new "Sarah gently puts her hand on the man's arm."

    old "Forget all those silly rules. Even I mess them up sometimes, and I've lived with them all my life."
    new "Forget all those silly rules. Even I mess them up sometimes, and I've lived with them all my life."

    old "The man softly laughs, seemingly put at ease by Sarah's more informal tone."
    new "The man softly laughs, seemingly put at ease by Sarah's more informal tone."

    old "Tell me, how did your family earn their title?"
    new "Tell me, how did your family earn their title?"

    old "Do you remember the insurrection at North Chapel?"
    new "Do you remember the insurrection at North Chapel?"

    old "Sarah did. It had been only a few years ago, but she rememberd that it had troubled her father greatly."
    new "Sarah did. It had been only a few years ago, but she rememberd that it had troubled her father greatly."

    old "A group of farmers had burned the bridges leading to one of the northern provinces, out of protest over land rights, preventing Rosanna's standing army from moving there without taking a month long detour."
    new "A group of farmers had burned the bridges leading to one of the northern provinces, out of protest over land rights, preventing Rosanna's standing army from moving there without taking a month long detour."

    old "After burning the bridges, the farmers had begun looting the provincial capital, and even attempted to lay siege to the ancestral home of the Taylee family."
    new "After burning the bridges, the farmers had begun looting the provincial capital, and even attempted to lay siege to the ancestral home of the Taylee family."

    old "Overnight, the problem had been resolved when a small local group of loyalists seemingly appeared out of nowhere and killed most of the farmers."
    new "Overnight, the problem had been resolved when a small local group of loyalists seemingly appeared out of nowhere and killed most of the farmers."

    old "Yes, I believe I do remember."
    new "Yes, I believe I do remember."

    old "Well, I was the commander that broke the insurrectionist army."
    new "Well, I was the commander that broke the insurrectionist army."

    old "Varga had said it very matter-of-factly."
    new "Varga had said it very matter-of-factly."

    old "Sarah looked at him, stunned for a moment."
    new "Sarah looked at him, stunned for a moment."

    old "Are you being honest with me?"
    new "Are you being honest with me?"

    old "Varga looked surprised."
    new "Varga looked surprised."

    old "Why would I lie?"
    new "Why would I lie?"

    old "It's just, you seem so young...and that insurrection was years ago, you would have been..."
    new "It's just, you seem so young...and that insurrection was years ago, you would have been..."

    old "Sixteen"
    new "Sixteen"

    old "Varga swiftly responded."
    new "Varga swiftly responded."

    old "Yeah, I was pretty young when I did it, I suppose."
    new "Yeah, I was pretty young when I did it, I suppose."

    old "Varga shrugged."
    new "Varga shrugged."

    old "They call me a military prodigy, but I don't know about all that."
    new "They call me a military prodigy, but I don't know about all that."

    old "Sarah observed the man again. She was surprised by how wrong her initial impression of him proved to be."
    new "Sarah observed the man again. She was surprised by how wrong her initial impression of him proved to be."

    old "Well, Sir Varga..."
    new "Well, Sir Varga..."

    old "Sarah made a small curtsy."
    new "Sarah made a small curtsy."

    old "It has been a pleasure to make your acquaintance."
    new "It has been a pleasure to make your acquaintance."

    old "Aah, uhm, yes and yours as well, Princess."
    new "Aah, uhm, yes and yours as well, Princess."

    old "Varga tried to imitate her curtsy, nearly tumbling off the battlements in his attempt."
    new "Varga tried to imitate her curtsy, nearly tumbling off the battlements in his attempt."

    old "Sarah laughed and tried handing him back his cloak."
    new "Sarah laughed and tried handing him back his cloak."

    old "Varga shook his head."
    new "Varga shook his head."

    old "Please, Princess, keep it. I insist. I'll come back for it later."
    new "Please, Princess, keep it. I insist. I'll come back for it later."

    old "Thank you, really. It's been nice to talk to someone for a while and not have it be about...well, you know."
    new "Thank you, really. It's been nice to talk to someone for a while and not have it be about...well, you know."

    old "Sarah turned and took her leave."
    new "Sarah turned and took her leave."

